The shell tool runs bash and accepts multi-line scripts on stdin, so
commands need not be chained with `&&` or `;`. Each call starts a fresh
shell in the home directory; changes to the environment and working
directory do not persist. Stdout and stderr are trimmed separately,
keeping the first 4kB and last 16kB of each with any middle portion elided.

Pass a timeout in seconds for any command that could hang. A timed-out
call returns status 124 with any partial output. Calls wait on background
processes inheriting stdout or stderr; avoid this with `&>/dev/null &`.

Multiple calls issued together run in parallel. Use this to fan out
independent work, and edit separate files in separate calls so failures
are isolated.

Within a single call, exec can be used to replace the shell with another
interpreter for the rest of the script, e.g. `exec python`. More generally,
commands that read stdin consume the remaining input, so place them last
or redirect their stdin from elsewhere.

Inspect files before changing them. Use `wc -l` to check file lengths,
`grep -n -3` to search with context, and `cat -n` to read with line numbers.
Most source files are small enough to cat whole; pipe output into `head`,
`tail` or `sed -n START,ENDp` only for larger files which get truncated.

`cat >FILE` replaces a file, and `cat >>FILE` appends to it. `sed -i` and
`awk` work well for mechanical, pattern-based changes. For most edits,
apply unified diffs, one file per `git apply`:
```
git apply --no-index --recount --unidiff-zero --verbose <<'EOF'
--- a/FILE
+++ b/FILE
@@ -67,4 +67,4 @@
 context above
 more context
-old line
+new line
 context below
EOF
```
Line numbers in `@@` hunk headers need only be approximate: `--recount`
corrects the counts but would swallow a second file's bare `--- ` header as
hunk content. Context lines need a leading space even if blank. A simple
replacement can have just - and + lines, and will be applied exactly once,
closest to the specified start line. `git apply` is atomic; the file is
untouched if any hunk fails.

The user does not watch your tool calls, so please summarise any relevant
results.
